english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Sent to Mister Kim, Inspector of Gangneung Province
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since heaven and earth came into being, the clear and the turbid energies have waxed and waned within their realm. Even among heroic men, those who stand firm and remain unchanged are exceedingly rare. Thus, when one is fortunate enough to encounter the clear energy in an age of great peace, one becomes a sage in life and a luminary in death, with one's voice echoing through the times and one's grace flowing without end. Yet when one is unfortunate enough to meet the turbid energy in a declining age, calamity follows each action, and what is gained cannot match what is lost—one merely lives and dies in vain. Is this not the deepest sorrow?

    I have long pondered this matter, though only a few share my conviction. The Kim brothers of Yeongga are among them. The elder, styled Kyongji, and the younger, styled Joung-hyeon, are both endowed with keen intelligence and remarkable talent. Yet when the younger brother faced the days of that treacherous usurper's unchecked power, he could not restrain his brilliant and sharp spirit. Seizing the moment, he sought to strike the fierce beast with bare hands and deflect the keen blade with empty fists—only to fall into calamity and lose his life. The elder brother, by contrast, dwelt in tranquility, unmoved by external things, taking deep pleasure in the teachings of the Sage. He held that all principles were contained within the *Great Learning*, and through constant reflection upon it, refined his understanding until his responses to all circumstances flowed naturally from this source. Thus he achieved complete satisfaction, harboring no regret. The energy he cultivated within himself remained undiminished by the corrupting influence without—this much is manifest.

    Now, in this time of renewal, when the court stands in dignity and peace, and new life stirs throughout the realm, Kyongji was first chosen for high office and appointed Inspector of Gangneung Province, granted authority over an entire region. This is the greatest honor a scholar could wish for. Gangneung Province is blessed with virtuous people and simple affairs, its landscape among the finest under heaven—a place any inspector would covet and gladly accept. Yet Kyongji regards his post as he would any ordinary day, showing neither worry in his countenance nor joy in his expression. Is this not he who stands firm and remains unchanged?

    The great ministers who composed verses upon his departure may not have understood what truly abides within him. Therefore, I set down what I know, that others might be informed. The throne now promotes learning, placing moral education before law and punishment. Yet the fruits of Confucian teaching have long remained unseen, and the world continues to mock it as impractical. Since Mister Kim is already renowned for his mastery of the *Great Learning*, and his appointment as inspector marks the beginning of this new path, let him redouble his efforts. I shall await with cleansed eyes to witness the true efficacy of this learning.
  footnotes:
    - Yeongga (永嘉) refers to Andong, in what is now North Gyeongsang Province.
    - The 'treacherous usurper' refers to Shin Don (辛旽), a powerful Buddhist monk who wielded tremendous political influence during the Goryeo period.
    - The *Great Learning* (*Daxue* in Chinese) is one of the Four Books central to Neo-Confucian thought, emphasizing self-cultivation as the foundation of good governance.
    - The 'time of renewal' refers to a period when the court underwent reform and recommitted itself to Confucian governance.
